ğŸ“¦ 6ï¸âƒ£ 2D Grid â€“ Counting Submatrices That Sum to Target
ğŸ¯ Problem: Given a matrix grid[][] and integer target, count the number of submatrices that sum to target.

This is a 2D version of Subarray Sum Equals K using prefix sum + hashing.

ğŸ”— LeetCode: 1074. Number of Submatrices That Sum to Target

âœ… Intuition:
Fix top and bottom rows.

Compress columns to 1D sum.

Apply prefix sum with hashmap on each compressed array.

ğŸ’»âœ¨ Java Code:
java
Copy
Edit
// â­ï¸ Count submatrices that sum to target
public int numSubmatrixSumTarget(int[][] matrix, int target) {
    int m = matrix.length, n = matrix[0].length;
    int res = 0;

    // Calculate prefix sums for rows
    for (int[] row : matrix) {
        for (int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
            row[j] += row[j - 1];
        }
    }

    // Iterate over all column pairs
    for (int startCol = 0; startCol < n; startCol++) {
        for (int endCol = startCol; endCol < n; endCol++) {
            Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
            map.put(0, 1);
            int currSum = 0;

            for (int row = 0; row < m; row++) {
                int sum = matrix[row][endCol] - (startCol > 0 ? matrix[row][startCol - 1] : 0);
                currSum += sum;
                res += map.getOrDefault(currSum - target, 0);
                map.put(currSum, map.getOrDefault(currSum, 0) + 1);
            }
        }
    }

    return res;
}
ğŸ’¡ Why Hashing?
We compress the 2D problem into a 1D prefix sum problem.

HashMap helps track how many times a sum has occurred â€” same as in 1D prefix tricks.

ğŸ­ 7ï¸âƒ£ Hashing with Custom Keys (Tuple/Pair Keys)
Problem: Count rectangles with equal area or same rows.

ğŸ”— LeetCode Example: Equal Row and Column Pairs â€“ #2352

ğŸ’¡ Hashing Trick:
Use stringified rows as keys in HashMap!

You can also hash custom pairs (a, b) by converting them to string.

ğŸ’»âœ¨ Java Code:
java
Copy
Edit
// â­ï¸ Count equal row-column pairs
public int equalPairs(int[][] grid) {
    int n = grid.length;
    Map<String, Integer> rowMap = new HashMap<>();

    // Hash each row
    for (int[] row : grid) {
        String key = Arrays.toString(row);
        rowMap.put(key, rowMap.getOrDefault(key, 0) + 1);
    }

    int count = 0;

    // Compare each column with rows
    for (int col = 0; col < n; col++) {
        int[] colArr = new int[n];
        for (int row = 0; row < n; row++) {
            colArr[row] = grid[row][col];
        }
        String colKey = Arrays.toString(colArr);
        count += rowMap.getOrDefault(colKey, 0);
    }

    return count;
}
ğŸŒŒ 8ï¸âƒ£ HashMap + Bitmasking (Advanced Trick)
Use HashMap where keys are bitmasks â€” useful for subsets, palindromes, words, etc.

ğŸ”— Example: 1178. Number of Valid Words for Each Puzzle

âœ¨ Highlight: Using bitmask as key!
